{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01XA773814ijugEgd4CZCsVA","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The openssl-toolbox pod doesn't exist yet. I need to create it. Let me plan the TLS migration:\n\n1. Generate certificates using an openssl-toolbox pod\n2. Create Kubernetes secrets with the certificates\n3. Update the StatefulSet to use secure mode with the certificates\n4. Restart the pods to pick up the new config\n\nThe plan for CockroachDB TLS migration:\n1. Create a CA certificate\n2. Create node certificates for each CRDB node\n3. Create a client certificate for the root user\n4. Store them in Kubernetes secrets\n5. Update the StatefulSet to mount the certs at `/cockroach/cockroach-certs` and switch from `--insecure` to `--certs-dir=/cockroach/cockroach-certs`\n\nNow I'll create the openssl-toolbox pod and generate the necessary certificates: a CA certificate with its key, node certificates signed by the CA with SANs for all node addresses, and a client certificate for the root user.\n\nI should use the `cockroach cert` command directly from one of the existing pods to generate these certificates, then create Kubernetes secrets to store them and update the StatefulSet to mount those secrets and enable secure mode.\n\nGenerating certificates with kubectl exec... I'm realizing the openssl-toolbox pod mentioned in the task might not actually exist yet, so I should work with what's available. Since the CockroachDB pods already have the `cockroach` binary, I can use those directly to generate the certificates—that's actually the standard approach anyway. My plan is to leverage the existing pods and the `cockroach cert` commands to handle the certificate generation.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":524,"cache_read_input_tokens":31069,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_i